<br>
It really isn't that hard to keep track of who is up for what and when.  Any time I am close to being up for a rotation that my guild really benefits from, I always check what else the guild in front of us might be doing.  If guild_03 is in front of us for G/E as an example, I will look and see if they have anything else due on the same day...if they are due for G/E, HP, Blood, VT, Shei, NToV, Dain, and KT (obviously can be any combo of any rotations), then I will make sure to ask them which they plan to get to.  If they say they are skipping some and doing others, I will prep as needed.  If they say they will get to them all, I'd definitely watch their progress because it would be impossible to get all of that done in time (unless playing 24/7).  I think most others would watch that kind of thing in at least some way.<br>
<br>
My point there is that yes, others are usually paying attention to what a guild is doing, especially if they are up for several rots at once (Even if it's a simple &quot;Hey, did you guys get to mob_x tonight?&quot;).  So I think if a guild was doing a 2 day rot, other guilds would have a pretty good idea when they started, and be able to know when they should be out of the zone.  You're allowed to wait up to 24 hours to enter NToV after a patch because of the randomness of the spawns, and after that you are given 48 hours to kill the mobs.  So I guess I don't see the problem with killing mobs c, d, or q during that 48 hours as long as you STOP killing in NToV (VT for 3 days) once those 48 hours are up.  After all, you have 24 hours from spawn to kill regular rot mobs, and I could see 5+ single rot mobs killed in the same day...and if they all popped at the same time you still have every bit of that 24 hours to kill as many of them as you are up for.<br>
<br>
It looks to me like this rule sprung forth from the old Trak/VS convention, but I really don't think that should be set as the standard for multiple day rotations.  With Trak and VS it involved a non-rotation mob so those rotation guilds agreed that it would be easier to just have that convention than form a rotation on VS...that's the same thing as leaving many/most of the flag mobs today off rotation so that it is easier on all of those involved.  I guess my point is that just because a convention (a convention used on a non-rot mob as well) has been used on something in the past that it shouldn't necessarily be applied to other things in the future (especially when they have totally different circumstances).  It might have been the perfect solution for Trak and VS but that doesn't mean it's perfect for multiple day rotations.<br>
<br>
From what Karadin said in his first reply to this thread, it seems to me like NB was forced to pass on a different rotation on their first VT run, and that's when this multi-day rotation rule came into effect.  It was never in place before (I understand the logic came from the old convention) which is why a couple of NToV runs ago we finished clearing the first day of NToV, went and finished the day killing CT with our mage camped up in NToV still...then we CoHed up the next day to finish like we would have had we killed CT or not.  The NToV mobs wouldn't have died any faster because we were at the only safe place I know of to camp a mage in NToV (and there was no way we could have finished clearing that day) and CT died as well all in our given time frame.<br>
<br>
I guess I don't understand why NB would have had to pass on a mob during their VT run or we would have needed to pass CT that time.  Again, VoF wont be doing VT, and hardly cares much about NToV anymore, so I don't argue this because I think my guild is being held back...I just don't understand why the above situation wouldn't be acceptable.  If the logic came from sharing the content, then no one should ever be able to kill more than 1 rot mob per day.  Yes, back in Kunark there were only 2 raid mobs, so the convention made sense...but nowadays there is plenty to go around.  If the convention is applied to multi-day rots on the basis that it's not fair to get those mobs as well as your other mobs on the same day, then it should be applied to single mob rots as well.  Maybe it takes some guilds an entire night to kill one mob.  If so they used their rightful time and killed their mob.  Guilds that don't need the same time to kill that one mob shouldn't be held back from killing another mob though (and they aren't), and the same should be applied for multiple mob rotations.  The time limits were made what they were for a reason (so I'm sure they were well thought out).  Guilds that need all of the time should be given it, and guilds that don't need all of it should ALSO be given it (IE kill whatever they can, as long as they leave said zone within their time limit)<br>
<br>
Not trying to stir things up, I just don't see the need for the rule. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#222222><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kelonybc>KelonYBC</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Shadows of Yamabushi</span><br>  Posts: 58<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(5/22/03 10:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=342.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Some Curiosities about RTA Rules?</span><hr size=1> Thank you, Bogarthemule.  You so clearly expressed what I thought myself.   Once you enter a multi-day rotation (let's take NToV), you have 48 hours to kill everything there, without another guild able to enter.  The rules go even further and say no other guild may go in after you to are done there to &quot;clean up&quot;.  Every rotation that you managed to get on is giving you the right to kill that mob on your turn.  If you can do it within the 24 hour time frame for normal mobs after they spawn, then you have every right to do so, no matter what else you take.  You can kill half of NToV on day 1, port out, kill KT and Statue, and continue clearing NToV on day 2.  This is NOT unfair, you earned the right to kill all of those because you made it on rotation.  <br>
<br>
The rule in its present form is unnecessary.  As long as you can kill mobs within the time frame given (24 hours after knowing they are up), you have every right to do so, in whatever order you chose.  The only time you should pass on a mob is if doing another rotation prevents you from killing the mob within those 24 hours. <p><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><br>
